A CLT Airfield Maintenance sweeper truck was sweeping runway 18C for routine maintenance and exited the runway to allow RPA4648 to depart.  After the aircraft's departure, the sweeper truck returned to the runway and the driver found one small bird carcass on part of the runway that had previously been swept.  Because the carcass was not found until right after the departure of RPA4648 and the remains found were fresh, it is likely that RPA4648 struck the bird.  CLT Airside Ops personnel responded to the runway and retrieved the carcass.  A feather sample was collected and sent to the Smithsonian for analysis.  The flight continued to its destination (KEYW).  Unknown if the flight crew were aware of the strike and unknown what part of the aircraft struck the bird.  It is assumed no damage or effect on flight occurred.

STRIKE OCCURED BEFORE AIRPORT OPENING. BIRD CARCASS WAS DISCOVERED DURING MORNING AIRPORT SELF INSPECTION. TWO PLANES HAD TAKEN OFF PRIOR TO AIRPORT OPENING; CREWS OF BOTH WERE CONTACTED. CREW OF N260K VERIFIED THAT THEY HAD SEEN SIX BIRDS WHILE ON THERE TAKE OFF RUN BUT AT THE TIME DID NOT REALIZE THEY HAD STRUCK ONE. AFTER LANDING IN NEW BERN THEY DISCOVERED SIGNS OF A STRIKE ON THERE RIGHT PROP. PILOT IN COMMAND (A STRANATHAN) STATED THAT THERE WAS NO EFFECT ON FLIGHT. THE AIRCRAFT WAS FLOWN BACK TO ROCKY MOUNT-WILSON REGIONAL AIRPORT AS ORIGINALLY PLANNED AND HANGARED. THERE IS NO VISIBLE DAMAGE TO THE AIRCRAFT. ALSO NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED. THE BIRD CARCASS DID NOT SHOW ANY SIGNS OF SNARGE, HOWEVER IT APPEARED THAT THE BIRD DID HAVE A BROKEN NECK. I DID NOT SEE ANY SIGNS OF THE STRIKE ON THE PROP WHEN THE PLANE AND CREW RETURNED. KINGSBORO INDUSTRIAL PARK LLC

MULTIPLE SPECIES. The flight crew reported to ATC that the aircraft struck a bird at 1200ft AGL during departure climb from runway 18L approximately 1 mile from the airport.  The flight initially continued with flight crew advising ATC no adverse results from the strike, but flight crew eventually decided to return to CLT for a precautionary landing.  The aircraft landed without incident on runway 18C.  Post flight inspection found evidence of two strikes on the aircraft: one on the nose, and one on the Captain's side window on the fuselage.  CLT Airside Ops personnel collected a tissue sample from each of the identified strikes and both samples collected were sent to the Smithsonian for analysis.  No damage was found on the aircraft.Smithsonian Wildlife Identification Comments: Two bags remains received. Bag 1 (pilot side) = Gray Catbird. Bag 2 (nose) = Northern Parula

Flight crew declared an emergency after hearing what was suspected to be a tire exploding during take-off run on runway 36R at KCLT.  The aircraft continued take-off but returned to KCLT and landed without incident.  During approach to landing the flight crew advised CLT Air Traffic Control that the noise could have been the result of a bird strike.  Evidence of a strike was found on the nose of the aircraft during post-flight inspection and CLT Airside Ops personnel collected a tissue sample from the remains found that was sent to the Smithsonian for analysis.  Inspection of both the departure and arrival runways was completed but no other remains/evidence was found.  Inspection of the aircraft found damage to the pitot tube on the aircraft's nose (warping) which was likely from the strike and the aircraft was taken out of service to further assess if it required replacement.  Flight crew reported to CLT Airside Ops that the emergency was not a result of the bird and that they smelled burning in the cockpit which required the return to field.  Extent of damage and aircraft time out of service (if any) currently unknown.  Will attempt follow-up with airline maintenance to determine and will revise this report if necessary.;   12/09/2019 REVISION: changed previous wording in this section, flight crew remarked the bird was not their reason for declaring an emergency.  Also after multiple attempts with Piedmont Airlines contact, extent of damage/time out of service was not reported to CLT Airport.One strike affecting the nose and pitot tube. THREE PHOTOS.

The outbound flight crew reported to CLT ATC (departure control) that the aircraft struck a bird during takeoff climb from runway 36C near the departure end of the runway.  The flight continued to its destination (KBHM) and landed without incident.  CLT Airport Staff contacted BHM Airport Staff to see if anybody could meet the aircraft to collect remains and information, but by the time information had been relayed the aircraft had already left KBHM to return to KCLT.  Once back at KCLT the aircraft was inspected and evidence of the strike was found on the left side of the fuselage near the wing root.  CLT Airside Ops personnel collected a tissue sample that was sent to the Smithsonian for analysis.  Inspection of the arrival runway was completed both after report of strike on departure and after aircraft returned on next flight leg, but no other remains/evidence was found during either inspection.  No damage was found on the aircraft. Left side of the fuselage near wing root. SI ID= INSECT (Insect from the Order Odonata (dragonfly/damselfly).)

On landing roll two Turkey Vultures were observed on the runway centerline.  They scattered at the last minute but the subsequent arrival reported a large carcass on the runway.  We treated the incident as a strike.  The airport authority also found Robin carcasses on the runway.  I surmise that the Vultures were picking at the Robin carcasses that were lying on the runway at the moment of our arrival.   It is possible that the Robin(s) were struck, perhaps unknowingly, some time before.   This event certainly brings to light the need to promptly report even suspected strikes as small dead birds attract much larger scavengers. CLT AIRSIDE OPS REMARKS: Inspection of the arrival runway was completed following report of aircraft striking a large bird.  One large carcass was found and retrieved by CLT Airside Operations personnel from the runway and field identified as Turkey Vulture.  A feather sample was also collected and sent to the Smithsonian for species identification confirmation.  Runway 18R was closed for approximately 8 minutes for inspection and collection of remains.  Inspection of the aircraft post-flight found no remains or damage. NOTE: NUMBER STRUCK NOT REPORTED ASSUME 1.

WASHINGTON CENTER NOTIFIED ME AND FILLED OUT THE APPROPRIATE FORMS. Other Remarks: Flight Crew advised ATC (Washington Center) that the aircraft experienced a cracked windscreen as a result of a bird strike during take-off climb from KCLT.  The aircraft continued it's flight and landed without incident at the destination airport (KRDU).  CLT Airport Ops was not informed of the strike.  RDU Airport Ops was contacted within 24 hours and advised they were unaware of the strike, therefore no remains were collected for species ID.  Airline Maintenance confirmed the aircraft sustained a cracked windshield and was out of service for 8 hours for repairs related to the incident.  Total estimated cost of repairs was not given.  No remains were collected for species ID by Airline Maintenance either. 10/08/2018 REVISION - Per Airline Maintenance, aircraft was out of service for a total of 25 hours for inspections and repairs related to the strike.  Repair made was replacement of the FO's windshield.  Estimated cost of repairs was not provided to CLT Airport Ops.

During inspection, evidence of at least 11 strikes were found on the nose/radome, fuselage, right and left wings of the aircraft. According to additional reports, aircraft was taken out of service for a reported 9.5 hours for inspection related to the strikes but no damage was found on the fuselage or the #1 engine after borescope.. deer struck right wing of aircraft damaging leading edge slat and leading edge;return to field  KCLT AIRPORT OPS REMARKS - Flight Crew reported to ATC hearing a loud bang during takeoff run from runway 36C and continued with the takeoff while declaring that the aircraft would return to the airport for a precautionary landing.  ATC was informed by another flight crew on taxi that they witnessed PSA 5320 hit a deer.  KCLT Airport Operations personnel responded to runway 36C and retrieved the remains of one deer from the runway.  The aircraft returned to KCLT and completed a low pass over runway 36R for inspection for damage and was observed to be actively leaking fuel from the  right wing.  The aircraft returned to runway 36R and made an emergency landing, exiting the runway onto taxiway R while continuing to leak fuel.  ARFF responded and sprayed the area with foam while the aircraft was evacuated.  All passengers were returned to the airport terminal via bus.  All fuel was drained from the aircraft before it was towed to maintenance for further inspection and repair.  Substantial damage was found on the right wing of the aircraft with initial estimated time out of service of 14 days (336 hours) and initial estimated cost of repair of $500,000 (both estimates provided by airline maintenance).  Flight Crew reported to KCLT Airport Operations personnel that they did not see any deer/wildlife during takeoff run but did feel an impact.  Will revise this report with additional information if necessary.

Evidence of a strike was found on the wing of the aircraft during inspection between flights.  KCLT Airport Operations personnel responded to the gate to obtain information but the inbound Flight Crew had already left the aircraft.  A tissue sample was collected from the aircraft which was sent to the Smithsonian for analysis.  Inspection of the runway the aircraft arrived on was also completed but no other remains/evidence was found.  The KCLT Airport Wildlife Coordinator reviewed ATC transmissions around the time the aircraft arrived that were downloaded from liveatc.net.  These transmissions revealed that a separate aircraft reported to ATC that there were birds on short-final approach at 100ft AGL.  This warning was given to AAL2054 and several other aircraft on final approach.  Additionally, AAL2054 reported to ATC that there were birds at 300ft AGL on short-final approach just left of the localizer.  AAL2054 did NOT report striking a bird to ATC but because of these transmissions it is likely the strike found on the wing of the aircraft occurred during final approach to land on runway 36R at KCLT.  No damage to the aircraft was reported.

ENGINE WAS SHUT DOWN AND THE FIRE SWITCH WAS PULLED. FIRE EXTINGUISHER BOTTLES WERE NOT USED.  ENG MANU DOES NOT CONSIDER THIS MAJOR ENGINE DAMAGE AS FAN BLADES WERE CHANGED BUT THE BORESCOPE HAD NO FINDINGS. THE #1 IDG AIL/OIL COOLER WAS REPLACED AND THE ENTIRE SET OF FAN BLADES (24) WAS REPLACED. ABOUT 10 MINUTES AFTER DEPTR THE CREW REPTD THEY LOST THE #1 ENG AND RETD TO ARPT.  PREC LDG AND DAMAGE TO ENGINE WERE NOT DUE TO BIRDSTRIKE ACCORDING TO ENG MANU. SERVICE DIFFICULTY REPORT STATES THAT UNVERIFIED INFORMATION SUBMITTED BY THE AVIATION COMMUNITY INDICATES DURING TAKE OFF, THE FLIGHT CREW HEARD A LOUD BANG. SHORTLY THEREAFTER ENGINE #1 EGT BEGAN TO CLIMB OUT OF LIMITS. FLT CREW SHUT DOWN ENG #1 AND RETURNED TO DEPARTURE ARPT. MX FOUND METAL IN THE TAIL PIPE. EVIDENCE OF BIRD IN INLET CONE AREA. ENG WILL BE REPLACED. AIRPORT INCIDENT REPORT STATES PILOT REPORTED HEARIND A LOUD NOISE UPON T/O FROM RDU AND NOW HEADING BACK. PILOT STATES TO ATC IT COULD HAVE BEEN A BLOWN TIRE AND PLANS TO CONDUCT A FLY BY WITH LANDING GEAR DOWN FOR GROUND EMERGENCY UNITS AT ATCT TO CHECK. F/O ALSO REPORTS SEEING A BIRD GO BY THE LEFT SIDE. INCIDENT UPGRADED TO AN ALERT II. PILOT REPORTS ENGINE #1 FAILED ON BASE AND PERFORMED SHUTDOWN TO LAND NOW INSTEAD OF FLY-BY. A/C LANDED OVERWT. INSPN ENSURES NO FIRE. RWY SWEEP FOUND NOTHING. A/C TAXIED TO GATE. HOT BRAKE READING. F/O ASKS CFR TO STANDBY AS PRECAUTION.
